The analysis showed the threshold at which underperforming retail would cease to be economically feasible. To offset the retail loss, the apartment unit rents would need to increase by 0.58% per square foot.  
Whether that increase is realistic would depend on supply and demand dynamics for apartment units in the housing submarket, which in turn would require analysis of factors including transporation access, availability of amenities such as a grocery store, convenience for commutes to employment centers, etc. 
Residual land value and feasibility analysis indicates when public capital would make a development concept pencil, but not whether it would be sound policy or smart politics to make such an investment. That is a determination that government officials must make relative to the government's economic and policy objectives. However, taxpayer dollars for development subsidies are in extremely high demand in municipalities across the country, and to use subsidies to cover costs in a development where residential tenants are already paying a premium to support negative retail would be dubious, at best, at a time of significant political attention on the need for greater subsidies to support creation of new affordable housing units.
